<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1940-04-16T11:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1940-04-16T11:00:00-05:00" n="588" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d588">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/2278:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extract]<note n="95" xml:id="d588fn95">Another
                                    section of this telegram is printed on <ref target="#pg_327">p.
                                        327</ref>.</note></seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1940-04-16T19:00:00+03:00">April 16,
                                    1940—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received 9:10 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>392. The Swedish Minister<note n="96" xml:id="d588fn96">Per Wilhelm
                                Gustaf Assarsson, since February 25, 1940.</note> told me the
                            following this morning in the strictest confidence.</p>
                        <p>1. He said he had learned from a member of the German Embassy that on the
                            day of the invasion of Denmark and Norway the German Ambassador had
                            called on Molotov and had advised him of the invasion (see my telegram
                            No. 361, April 9, noon<note n="97" xml:id="d588fn97">See footnote 91,
                                    <ref target="#pg_549">p. 549</ref>.</note>) giving Molotov an
                            assurance that Germany did not intend to invade or attack Sweden or
                            Finland and requesting and receiving a similar assurance from Molotov
                            with respect to Soviet intentions.</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . . . . . . . . .</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>